# AI Gateway component policy (`ai_gateway.mdc`)

The `ai_gateway/` folder at the MIDAS repo root is an **external git submodule** owned by the Unified-Cloud-DevOps team. It is treated as an opaque, read-only component.

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Upstream repository | `https://ucgithub.exlservice.com/Unified-Cloud-DevOps/bu-digital-exlerate-aigateway.git` |
| Tracked branch | `develop` |
| Mount point | `ai_gateway/` (top-level subfolder) |
| Mechanism | Git submodule (pinned to a specific upstream commit SHA) |
| Push URL | `DISABLED` (set via `git remote set-url --push origin DISABLED`) |
| Developer / architect guide | `.cursor/scratch/readme.md` (to be promoted to `docs/components/ai_gateway.md`) |

## Hard rules for AI agents and humans

1. **Do NOT edit any file under `ai_gateway/`** as part of MIDAS work. The folder is owned by an external repo. Edits there must go upstream first, then we re-pin via `git submodule update --remote`.
2. **Do NOT add `ai_gateway/**` paths to MIDAS-owned `deploy/`, `helm/`, `Jenkinsfile_*`, Terraform modules, or any MIDAS deploy code.** The AI Gateway brings its own `ai_gateway/deploy/`, `ai_gateway/helm/`, `ai_gateway/infra/terraform/` and will be deployed by a separate, dedicated Jenkins pipeline (TBD).
3. **Do NOT push from inside `ai_gateway/`.** The push URL is `DISABLED` so it will fail; do not re-enable it. Pushes to upstream are not part of MIDAS workflow.
4. **Do NOT delete, move, rename, or reinitialise the submodule** (no `git submodule deinit`, no `git rm ai_gateway`, no `rm -rf ai_gateway/.git`) without explicit user approval.
5. **Do NOT change the tracked branch in `.gitmodules`** without explicit user approval.
6. **Do NOT commit MIDAS changes that depend on un-merged upstream behaviour.** If the upstream needs a change, that change must be merged upstream and pinned in MIDAS first.

## Allowed agent actions

- Refresh after a `git pull`: `git submodule update --init --recursive`.
- Inspect: `git submodule status`, `git -C ai_gateway log`, `git -C ai_gateway diff`, `cat ai_gateway/...`.
- Pull upstream + re-pin (when the user explicitly asks for a bump). Two supported methods:

  **Method A — one-liner (track-the-branch):**
  ```bash
  git submodule update --remote --merge ai_gateway
  git -C ai_gateway log --oneline -1
  git add ai_gateway
  git commit -m "ai_gateway: bump to $(git -C ai_gateway rev-parse --short HEAD)"
  ```

  **Method B — manual (recommended; lets you inspect before bumping):**
  ```bash
  git -C ai_gateway fetch origin
  git -C ai_gateway checkout develop
  git -C ai_gateway pull --ff-only
  git -C ai_gateway log --oneline <old-sha>..HEAD     # inspect
  git add ai_gateway
  git commit -m "ai_gateway: bump to <sha> (<summary>)"
  ```

  In both methods, `git push` from MIDAS only publishes the one-line MIDAS pin update; nothing in `ai_gateway/` is pushed (and even if attempted, push URL is `DISABLED`).

- Verify push is still disabled (run after every pull):
  ```bash
  git -C ai_gateway remote get-url --push origin   # must print "DISABLED"
  ```

- For coordinated changes (upstream bump + MIDAS-side change in the same PR), see `.cursor/scratch/readme.md` §6.6.

## When the agent must stop and ask the user

- The user requests an edit to a file under `ai_gateway/`.
- The user requests adding `ai_gateway/**` to MIDAS deploy code.
- A `git submodule update` would change the pinned SHA without an accompanying explicit user request to bump.
- The push URL is found to be anything other than `DISABLED`.

